        "text": "Judges 4:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Days when they were without the true God, without teaching prophets, and without law, Israel had already experienced in the times of defection after Joshua (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 2:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".), but will experience them in the future still oftener and more enduringly under the idolatrous kings in the Assyrian and Babylonian exile, and still even now in its dispersion among all nations. That this saying refers to the future is also suggested by the fact that Hosea (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 3:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") utters, with a manifest reference to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 15:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of our speech, a threat that the ten tribes will be brought into a similar condition (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 9:3-4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and even Moses proclaimed to the people that the punishment of defection from the Lord would be dispersion among the heathen, where Israel would be compelled to serve idols of wood and stone (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 28:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 28:64",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), i.e., would be without the true God. That Israel would, in such oppression, turn to its God, would seek Him, and that the Lord would be found of them, is a thought also expressed by Moses, the truth of which Israel had not only had repeated experience of during the time of the judges, but also would again often experience in the future (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
